Nemo 8/22/2023 7:16 PM
I'm not sure I can describe it in a way that most people will understand, because most don't think outside of the paradigm of local physics happening ex nihilo. However, I strongly hold that this view of our local physics is improbable. There are two routes I know of to show you something else. 1. More elegantly, the Mathematical Universe Hypothesis https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_universe_hypothesis which postulates that "everything exists" according to the grammar of mathematical structure. 2. Easy to understand, the simulation hypothesis/arguments that we live in a simulation https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simulation_hypothesis - of course, if this is a simulation, it is first and foremost YOU who find yourself in a simulation, any laws of physics, of base reality, are no longer accessible through empirical research and consensus. In short, if this is a simulation, well, the simulating reality might instead be operating in Conway's Game of Life, or any other compatible ruleset. We know that base reality gives rise to self-awareness because we are self-aware. Substructures of the base conditions acquire this property, some of the time. This is a very interesting property of a ruleset but if you follow Wolfram's work you may come to view this as intuitive. If we break down self-awareness, we find that what we mean by it is at its simplest, a heavy symbolic compression of a more intricate system (that is aware). Following the logic of the famous simulation argument and applying the anthropic principle, the most likely reality to be experienced is the substructure from the substrate that is most numerous, and the substructure that is most numerous is very much unknown to us right now, but we may estimate that one of the main reasons for it being numerous is self-replication, which is somewhat adjacent to possessing self-awareness.
7:17 PM
There are many more lines of thought and intuitions that I can talk about, but I think that my view is pretty abstract and distanced from consensus, I would be very surprised if I got across what I wanted here.

KIF17 interacts directly, via its tail part, with the PDZ domain of mLin-10 (Mint1/X11), which is a large protein complex in- cluding mLin-2 (CASK), mLin-7 (MALS/Velis), and the NR2B subunit [Setou et al., 2000]. The bond between KIF17 and Mint1 is regulated by CaMKII: phosphorylation at serine 1029 leads to breakup of the KIF17-Mint1 com- plex and resultant impaired transport [Guillaud et al., 2008]. Transgenic mice overexpressing KIF17 showed rapid learn- ing in behavioral tests, with good recall. These mice dis- played increased levels of transcription factor CREB and its phosphorylation [Wong et al., 2002].
